{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_broadwick_ver01/data/sn93065779/00279558236/1945082701/0349.xml":{"full_text":"LINCOLN COUNTY\u2019S FAVORITE FAMILY NEWSPAPER\nj\u201d\nLOCAL MARKETS.\nCOTTON 21 tic, 23c lb.\nWHEAT SI.CS bu.\nCORN *1.40 bu.\nEGGS 53c and 55c doz.\nMrs. Ceph Blanton, of Shelby,\nspent the week-end in Lincolnton as\nthe guest of Mrs. Edith Jetton.\nMiss Rosa Mae Shuford, of Shelby,\nspent the week-end in Lincolnton as\nthe guest of Mrs. Herbert Rodd.\nMrs. Francis H. Langley, of St.\nPetersburg, Fla., is the guest of Mrs.\nL. D. Warlick.\nAddress: William M. Nantz, S 2/c,\nWard 5 C, U.S.N.H., N. 0.8., Nor\n\"folk, 11, Va.\nMrs. P. A. Herman and son, Phil\nlip Morris, leave today for Rayville,\nGa., to visit relatives.\nMrs. J. L. Lattimore has returned\nto her home in Maiden after a visit\nto her sister, Mrs. J. W. Mullen.\nMr. and Mrs. Thos. S. Golden, of\nHickory, were guests yesterday of j\nMrs. Golden\u2019s mother, Mrs. R. C.\nGoode.\nMiss Eleanor Rodd ha s returned\nfrom Wilmington where she attend\ned a house party given by one of her\ncollege mates.\nMrs. W. M. Varner and daughter,\nMiss Edna Varner, of Lincolnton,\nRoute 3, were visitors in The Times\noffice Friday.\nMiss Annie Cline and Mrs. Eugene\nDorsey and son, Eddie, of Shelby,\nwere guests over the week-end of\nMr. and Mrs. Lee F. Cline.\nMrs. A. M. Cornwell and children, i\nMis s Beth and Milton Cornwell, left\nSaturday to spend a while at their\nsummer home at Chimney Rock.\nMrs. C. K. Spicer and daughter,\nMiss Martha Spicer, of Raleigh, are\nguests of Mrs. J. A. Lore. Mrs. Spi\ncer was formerly Miss Kitty Lore,\ndaughter of Mrs. Lore.\nPharmacist Mate A. Hal Cornwell,\nof the Brooklyn Navy Yard, is spend\ning a leave here. Mrs. Cornwell and\ndaughter, who are with relatives in\nPennsylvania, are expected to join\nhim here later.\nL. C. Hovis, S 1/c is spending a\ntwenty-day leave with his family and\nhis parents, Mr. and Mrs. L. C. Hovis.\nSeaman Hovis recently returned to\nthe States from the Pacific area. He\nsaw considerable action during the\nOkinawa campaign.\nPfc. George W. Punch, U.S.M.C.,\nhas returned to the States after 33\nmonths in the Pacific theatre. Pfc.\nPunch, who entered the service in\nOctober, 1942, served with an anti-!\naircraft artillery battalion while\noverseas. He is the son of Mr. and\nMrs. T. E. Punch, of Lincolnton,\nRoute 4.\nSgt. J. J. Wyckoff, Jr., who is beipg,\ntreated at Moore General hospital at\nSwannanoa, spent the week-end in\nLincolnton with his parents, Mr. an,!\nMrs. J. J. Wyckoff. Sgt. Wyckoff was\nrecently returned to the States and\nthis was his first visit home in two\nyears. His wife, who he married In\nBelfast, Ireland, expects to join him\nhere this fall.\nA WEATHER EYE\nU 0 ON TOUR LOAN COST\n=f The time to get out your pencil and\nI figure is before you borrow.\nI If you need to finance any per-\nM sonal need, ask us about a low-cost\npersonal bank loan first.\nIt may save you money.\nFirst National Bank\nlincolnton, n. c.\nofficers\nf\u00bb\u2022\nH. W. RUDISILL xmnam\nMr, and Mrs. G. S. Burgin spent\nthe week end in Hendersonville.\nMrs. D. W. Robinson, of Colum\nbia, S. C., is a guest at the home of\nMrs. H. S. Robinson.\nMr. and Mrs. Jack Kiser and fam\nily and Miss Jane Lohr spent the\nweek end in the mountains.\nMr. and Mrs. M. B. Winstead were\nin Davidson Sunday afternoon to see\ntheir son, Meldrum, who is a student\nat Davidson College.\nPvt. Dan Schronce, who has been\nspending a 30-day furlough with his\nmother, Mrs. Frank L. Schronce, on\nLincolnton, route 1, will leave to\nnight for the return trip to his camp.\nCapt. James F. Reinhardt, who\nrecently returned from overseas, is\nvisiting his parents. Mr. and Mrs. J.\nM. Reinhardt. His wife and daughter\nare here with him.\nThe outstanding event of the week\nis the Beauty Contest to be held to\nmorrow, Tuesday night, at the high\nj school auditourium under the aus\npices of the Parent-Teachers Asso\nciation. The curtain will rise at 8:15.\nAdmission will be 15 and 35 cents.\nThos. E. Seagle has been honorably\ndischarged from military service as-\nter serving nineteen months overseas 1\nas a mechanic in the 31st Ordnance, i\nHe holds the Good Conduct Medal,\nthe Campaign Medal with two bronze\nstars, and the American Defense\nMedal. He i s now at the home of\nhis parents, Mr. and Mrs. T. P. i\nSeagle, on Lincolnton, Route 2. 1\nMr. and Mrs. L. J. Seagle, Jr., of i\nVale, Cpl. and Mrs. J. Everette Wise,\nlof Lincolnton, spent several days last\nweek in the mountains of North\nI Carolina and Tennessee. Cpl. Wise\nrecently returned to the States from i\nthe European theatre of war where I\nhe spent six and one-half months, i\nAt the expiration of his thirty-day 1\nfurlough he will return to Ft. Bragg.\nN. C., for reassignment. Mrs. Wise\nwill continue to make her home with\nMr. and Mrs. Dean Guest on 307\nNorth Grove street, Lincolnton. I\ni\nJunior Series Opens\nTonight In Charlotte i\nI \u2014TT VHS I\nA number of Lincolnton people are 1\nplanning to go to Charlotte tonight\nfor the opening of the Junior World 1\nSeries, national finals in American\nLegion Junior baseball, one of the 1\ncountry\u2019s top sports events of the\nyear, at Griffith Park. The game be\ngins at 8:00 p. m. Governor Gregg\nCherry i s scheduled to toss out the 1\nfirst ball, with Victor Johnson, state\nLegion department commander, catch\ning it.\nTrenton, N. J., and Oak Park, 111.. 1\nmeet in the opening game tonight\ni with Shelby, North Carolina\u2019s hope I\nIto bring the championship to this\nstate, battling the big Tucson, Ariz.,\nteam tomorrow night in the second\ngame. Six games are scheduled in the\ndouble elimination series. A seventh\ngame, if necessary, will be played on\nMonday, September 3, Labor Day.\nHUSBANDS TO BURN\nLady: I see by the paper that a\nwoman in Omaha just cremated her\nfourth husband.\u201d\nOld Maid: \u201cIsn\u2019t that always the\nway! Some of us can\u2019t get a man\nwhile others have husbands to burn.\nTHE LINCOLN TIMES, LINCOLNTON, N. C., MONDAY, AUGUST 27, 1945\nAwarded Bronze Star\njwsmp a\nPfc. William Claude Rudisill,\nabove, has been awarded the Bronze\nStar for outstanding performance of\nduty, according to a letter received\nby his uncle, C. Flay Houser of Lin\ncolnton, Route 3. Pfc. Rudisill is\nalso the holder of the driver\u2019s medal,\nthe good conduct medal, the pre-Pearl\nHarbon ribbon, and the ETO ribbon\nwith 5 battle stars.\nPfc. Rudisill is with the 94th Ar\nmored Field Artillery battalion and\nhis citation reads:\n\u201cFor heroic service while in action\nagainst the enemy from July 17, 1944,\nuntil 8 May, 1945. Pfc. Rudisill, in\nthe capacity of driver of the 1-4 ton\nwire vehicle of Battery B, 94th Ar\nmored Field Artillery Battalion, has\ndistinguished himself by his ingen\nuity, courage and devotion to duty on\nmany different occasions.\n\u201cAt Troyes, France, on 24 August,\n1944, the firing position of Battery B\nwas heavily shelled by German ar\ntillery and a number of men in the\narea were wounded. With complete\ndisregard for his own safety, and\nwhile enemy shells were still falling\nin the area, Pfc. Rudisill drove his\nvehicle directly through the path of\nfire to the side of the wounded men,\nwhom he then evacuated to the more\nprotected position of the battalion\naid station. Again on the 5 Octo\nber, 1944, at Arracourt, France, dur\ning an extremely heavy shelling of\nthe \u201cB\u201d Battery area, six cannoneers\nwere seriously wounded, Pfc. Rudi-\nsill, driving his vehicle along a route\nwhich was covered by a hail of en\nemy fire, evacuated two of the men\nto the battalion aid station in the\nrear. Then at great risk to himself,\nhe returned along this same route to\nhis battery area where he evacuated\ntwo more of the wounded. Pfc. Rudi\nsill has conclusively proved that he\nplaces the lives of his comrades and\nthe success of his battalion far and\nabove any risk to his ow n person.\u201d\nMiss Nancy Ingle\nTo Wed Bill Louis\nMrs. J. B. Smith, of this city, an\nnounces the engagement of her 1\ngranddaughter, Miss Nancy Ingle, to\nBill Louis, petty officer, second class, 1\nof Gastonia. The wedding will take\nplace on Tuesday, August 28th.\nMiss Ingle is the daughter of Mrs.\nEthel Smith Ingle.\nCinder Construction\nProvides Advantages j\n\nNorth Carolina farmers are be-\ncoming more interested in the use of j\ncinder and concrete blocks in the 1\nconstruction of farm buildings, and j\nmany questions have been coming to\nState College in regard to certain\nfeatures of this type of construe-\ntion.\nProf. David S. Weaver, agricultur-\nal engineer of the State College Ex\ntension, ha s released the following\ninformation concerning the matter:\nIn general either cinder blocks or\nconcrete blocks can be used with suc\ncess for farm buildings. It is true\nthat any type of masonry construc\ntion will have a different effect on\ntemperature and moisture conditions\nthan frame construction. However,\nhere in the South where we do not\nhave the extremely low temperatures,\nthese differences are not enough to\ncause concern.\nThe advantages of masonry con\nstruction as compared to frame con\nstruction are several, chiefly, freedom\nfrom decay, and termite and rodent\ndestruction. They need not be paint\ned and should last indefinitely. At\nthe present time they compare fa\nvorably with frame construction in\nprice although this may change as\nlumber again becomes more plenti\nful.\nCinder blocks are relatively new in\nuse, and there is always the ques\ntion as to whether or not the^-are\ncompletely weather proof. It has\nbeen shown that there is a definite\nneed for treating the outside surface\nof cinder blocks if a one hundred\nper cent water proof wall is needed.\nThi 3 particularly true if an at\ntempt is made to plaster the inside\nsurface of a cinder block wall.\nAny good building supply dealer\ncan furnish a cinder block weather\nproofing compound. Most of these\ncompounds are in the form of pow\nder and need to be mixed with water\nand applied at a thick cream con\nsistency with an ordinary paint\nbrush. Usually two or more coats\nare needed for the best waterproof\ning.\nIf you don\u2019t read the Times you\n\u25a0an\u2019t be very well posted on local\nind national happenings, because no\nither newspaper published in Lincoln\n\u2022ounty give s y ou the news and ad\nvertising coverage Times readers get.\nSwine Brucellosis is on the in\ncrease in this country and is caus\ning seriou s damage to farmers.\nLt. Lineberger Writes Another\nLetter Telling His Experiences\nEditor\u2019s Note: This is the fourth\nin the series of letters written by\nCapt. Robert H. Lineberger to his\nmother, Mrs. B. C. Lineberger, de\nscribing his experiences when his\nplane was forced down over China.\n\u201cWhat a day yesterday was! In\ncelebration of Air Force Day we set\nout to break all the records for get\nting stuff across the Hump to China,\nand we did. I worked in operations\nfor eleven and one-half hours. They\nserved food on the line\u2014to mechan\nics and men loading ships. The band\nplayed in front of operations. To\nsave time lost on the ground in\nChina all crews took along box\nlunches.\n\u201cWe saw miracles yesterday. Ships\nwere loaded and serviced and were\ngone again before the crew that\nbrought the ship in could reach op\nerations. I can\u2019t give any figures\nbut we put, I imagine, over a week\u2019s\ntonnage over the rock pile in one day.\nNaturally, everyone from the C. O.\ndown to the newest buck private\nfeels pretty proud today.\n\u201cI\u2019ll be going o n leave tomorrow.\nI\u2019m going to spend several days vis\niting with Walker and Jerry. Then\n1 11 go on the. rest camp for the bal\nance of my fifteen days.\n\u201cI think I forgot to tell you that\nI had a bunch of packages waiting\nwhen I came back Saturday. Every\nthing tasted doubly good.\n\u201cTo save me I can\u2019t figure out how\nyou have the idea that I\u2019ll be home\nin September. January still looks\nlike the date to me.\n\u201cNow to get on with the story of\nmy trip. I hope you will save these\nletters. I haven\u2019t had a chance to\nwrite everything in my diary and I\ndon\u2019t imagine I\u2019ll ever get around to\nit. Before the only Chinese I had\nseen were the coolies, who unloaded\nour planes, but I think my experi\nence has given me a much better idea\nof what China and the Chinese people\nare really like.\n\u201cJoe\u2019s mother had a beautiful pair\nof jade earrings which I compliment\ned. I had the idea of maybe buying\n*ume, but they said there was no\njade around that part of the country.\nThat is, after about fifteen minutes\nof gestures, etc., they got the idea\nacross. During our whole stay in\nChina we never did meet anyone who\nspoke enough English to do away\nwith gestures and drawings.\n\u201cFor dinner we had chicken, pota\ntoes, boiled turnips, fried pork, what\nI\u2019d swear was some C ration meat,\ntea, and more corn liquor. Once again\nwe had an audience who watched us\neat, and then sat down at the table\nafter we had finished. This night\nwe decided to turn the tables and\nwe watched them while they ate.\nWith about six people eating, the\nchopsticks moved across the table so\nfast it\u2019s a wonder someone didn\u2019t\nlose a hand.\n\u201cAs soon as he finished eating Joe\nretired to a sort of couch in a corner\nof the room. There he proceeded to\nset up his opium equipment. I\u2019d\nnever thought opium smoking was so\ncomplicated. First he heated the\nopium over a little lamp. As it be-\ncame soft he would roll it on a little\nblock of stone until it wa s shaped\nmor e or less like a ball. Then he\u2019d\ntransfer it to another metal rod, beat\nit again and place it in the pipe.\nThere was only a small opening in\nthe pipe bowl and the opium placed\nthere had ,jto have a small hole\nthrough the center for air to enter.\nThe pipe is held very close to the\nlamp\u2019s flame and the fire is sucked\nthrough the opium, burning it on the\nway. I\n\u201cChiang Soong Fa and the other\nsoldier boy, Doa Si Dow, kept ask\ning us to sing. We finally gave them\na couple chords of \u2018Pistol Packing\nMama,\u2019 and \u2018l\u2019ve Been Working on\nthe Railroad.\u2019 Not satisfied with\nthat they insisted that we dance for\nthem. None of us would do it again,\nbut the four of us made up a line\naround a little stool in the center of\nthe room. Everyone gathered around\nend watched wide-eyed. It occurred\nto us how silly we must look and we\nstopped in a hurry.\n\u201cSince it was still early for bed,\nwe made an attempt at talking and\ngiving some English lessons. When\nwe turned in Joe was still smoking\nhis pipe. There were the usual mos\nquitoes and bites. Once I got up to\nspread on some mosquito repellant,\nbut after that I slept fairly well.\n\u201cBreakfast was a bowl of sweet\negg custard. It was very good and\nfo r a change they didn\u2019t force more\nand more food on us. We were anx\nious to start on our way, because at\nthe leisurely rate we had been trav\neling it began to look as though we\u2019d\nbe weeks reaching I After\nbreakfast they explained that we\nwere going to Joe\u2019s brother\u2019s home.\nWhile they were getting the horses\nready we sat around speculating as\nto when we\u2019d get back to our base\nand trying to keep the flies brushed\naway. Before we left we gave some\n1 of the people shroud lines from a\nparachute and gave a parachute to\nJoe\u2019s wife. She brought out a huge\nbundle of Chinese money with which\nshe tried to pay us.\n1 \u201cAfter packing up our few belong\ning s we were on our way. The scen\nery was beautiful. We could see far\nacross the mountains and occasion\ni ally the curing rice paddies on the\nl sides of hills. In a gesture that in\neluded all we could see Joe said that\ni it belonged to him and his brother.\nWe were a little skeptical but, as we\ndiscovered later, he must have been\ntelling the truth.\n\u201cEvery now and then we would get\noff and walk for a while to rest the\nhorses, and mainly ourselves. Sev-\neral times we saw some pretty flow\ners and a couple of the boys picked\nthem for us. We couldn\u2019t very well\nthrow them away without their per\nhaps taking offense. I looked back\nonce and got a good laugh. Ed, the\nengineer, was riding just behind me.\nHe had a good growth of beard and\nl.ad needed a haircut before we left\noui base. There he was perched on\nthat little mule with a silly grin on\nhis face and with a big bunch of red\nand yellow flowers in one hand.\n\u201cOne of the soldiers and Joe\u2019s wife\nwere bringing up the rear, but they\nstayed out of sight most of the time.\nI never did find out why, but one\nman with a pistol and rifle led the\nprocession.\n\u201cFrom the top of one hill we could\nsee a little village on the side of the\nmountain. Doe Se Dow told us this\nwas where we were going. The whole\nvillage was out to meet us. They\nhad a pair of field glasses and must\nhave spotted u s long before we got\nthere. As at other places we didn\u2019t\nsee any girls or women. Every now\nand then we could see one peeking\naround a corner or out\u00bbof a window.\n\u201cThe new brother wa s dressed in\nAmerican style clothes and looked\nmore like an American than anyone\nwe had seen up till then. He had\non a wrist watch with a flexible band\nand tennis shoes. One of the men\nwith him displayed a jade tooth ev\nery time he smiled. Our new friend\u2019s\nname was Chung Soong Mong. Af\nter introductions and a lot of talk\ning back and forth we started to the\nhouse. It was at the highest part\nof the village.\u201d\n*L|J|\nWashington, D. C. \u2014All phases of\nthe problem of reconversion are be\ning given prior consideration in\nWashington. Other work has been\nput aside in order that various de\npartments can catch up with the\nspeed of the war and peace develop\nments.\nThe over-all picture, as gathered\nat Washington a s the war comes to\nan and, shows:\nSome five million workers will be\nlaid off at war plants. While some\nwill retire from the labor field, post- I\nwar industry will be able to employ\nmost of the balance.\nArmy and Navy has halted work\ninvolving more than 26 billion dol\nlars.\nThe war ha s cost nearly three hun\ndred billion dollars, in addition to\nthe quarter million dead \u2014a total cas\nualty list of more than one million.\nWhile the Treasury Department\ndoes not want a radical cut in taxes,\nit looks as K Congress will make\nsubstantial reductions. Government\nspending will be reduced, but will\ncontinue far above the prewar era.\nWar Production Board will expe\ndite manufacture of civilian goods,\nand of some sort will be provided by\nthe government during reconversion.\nTravel conditions will remain seri\nous for some months. With more\nthan five million men being discharg\ned during next 12 months, the Army\ntransportation demands will remain\ngreat. In addition closing of war\nplants will see thousands of families\nmoving back to their former homes.\nLong delayed travel holidays will be\nin order, placing additional tax on\ntransportation.\nThe 1945 food crop will be one of\nbiggest in history\u2014but rationing of\nfood will continue for some time.\nFood shipments to Europe will con\ntinue on big scale. Other rationing\nwill be dropped as soon ns possible.\nManpower controls will be revoked\nimmediately.\nCongress to return in session Sep\ntember 4th, to tackle these problems.\nMay pass law ending Selective Ser\nvice at once.\nPrice control will be lifted in in\ndividual items, a s soon as civilian\nproduction will prevent inflationary\npressure.\nAccelerated production of electri\ncal supplies is to be one of the most\noutstanding early results noted.\nSpecial supplies will be made avail\nable to those companies which can\nstart production immediately, with\nout delay caused by reconversion.\nSome will be able to start without\nmanpower layoff.\nReconversion blueprints for the\naicraft industry have already been\naircraft industry has actually start\ned on civilian planes\u2014soon to be on\nthe market at reasonable prices.\nThe adaptation of the atomic bomb\n1 to civilian industrial use is something\nto occur NOT in the near future.\nMonths, or even years, will be re\nquired.\nThe long-looked-for television is an\nearly possibility. Plans to inaugu\nrate television and FM broadcasting\nfrom stratosphere airplane s cruising\nsix miles in the air. Permits and\nequipment ar e promised in the near\nfuture.\nRadar, marvel of the war, will find\nmany uses in peace. Airports will\nutilize radar to bring plane s in safe\nly.\nTelephone development promises in\nthe near future include direct long\ndistance dialing. Individuals in New\nYork will be able to dial specific\nparty in San Francisco or elsewhere.\nRead the Want Ads in The Times.\nn\nOURS\nHAS BEEN A WAR JOB\nGoD has crowned our arms with victory and a\nstirring chapter in the history of our country comes\nto a close\u2014a chapter in which at all times you have\nmet war's all-out demands for telephone service with\nspeed and skill and devotion.\n\u201cThe determined manner in which telephone\nfolks accepted and discharged their high responsi\nbility\u2014the 3,705 who served as members of the\narmed forces and those of you who stayed at your\npost\u2014deserves the highest praise. You did your job\nwell and you made other important contributions\nthrough your splendid record of War Bond purchases,\nyour blood donations and other essential homefront\nactivities. With an overwhelming sense of pride in\nthe sort of folks you are I say, my sincere thanks to\nyou all.\n\u201cWith thankfulness in our hearts in the triumph\nof our Nation and its Allies, we look forward to the\nreturn of the men and women who left us to enter\nthe Armed Forces. We shall bear forever in our\nhearts the memory of those who made the Supreme\nSacrifice.\u201d\n\nPRESIDENT\nA public statement of appreciation\nmade by Hal S. Dumas to the more\nthan 36,000 Southern Bell employee*.\nSouthern Bell Telephone and Telegraph Company\nINCORPORATED\nANNOUNCEMENT\nBarbecue Stand\nChanges Hands\nWe have purchased the Eva Barbecue Stand on\nWater Street and will continue to operate the busi\nness in the same location, with the same well known\ncooks, etc., the only changes being the ownership and\nname; Serving the best meals, barbecue sandwiches,\ncold drinks, etc., it is possible to have.\nThe new name of the business will now be the\nLINCOLNTON BARBECUE STAND\nWe Will Appreciate Your Patronage.\nLINCOLNTON BARBECUE STAND\nJOE HAWKINS JOHN SCRUGGS\nLINCOLNTON, N. C.\nSBC DEPENDABILITY 3\u00a7j|E\n9bAVION.UI.tHi\nONE quarter of all Holland it\nbeneath the level of the tea\nprotected from the inrush\ning waters by. 1500 milet of\ndylceti It it the dependability\nof the dyke that hat made that\nland habitable.\nIt is the unswerving depenct\nability of our organization\nthat has won for us public con\nfidence. Each ceremony is a\ntribute of memorial dignity.\nijj l ll\nPAGE THREE","height":"20702","width":"14975"}}
